<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-398-220  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 398 220.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The New York Times  July 5 1989 v138 n47,922 pC3(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Mysterious waves may speed fiber optics; the contents of theLibrary of Congress might be transmitted in seconds. (BusinessTechnology) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Andrews, Edmund L.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Fiber-optic communications could be increased in speed ahundredfold by using a wave form known as a soliton.andP;  Solitons arefound throughout nature - in electricity, ocean currents,acoustics and light.andP;  Fiber optics is likely to be among the firstcommercial applications.andP;  Results indicate that it might bepossible to transmit data at 100G-bps.andP;  In contrast, data ontoday's fastest systems travels at 1.7G-bps.andP;  At issue aretechnologies such as: encyclopedia-sized data bases complete withsound and video transmitted in brief bursts of data; glossy photosrelayed over high-powered facsimile machines; and multiplechannels of two-way high-definition television.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber OpticsOptoelectronic DevicesNew TechniqueTelecommunicationsWaveformsFuture Technologies.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   A boost for fiber optics. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>